(Pretext Exciting new browser library from Cheng Lou, previously a React core developer and the) Tj
T*
(original creator of the react-motion animation library. Pretext solves the problem of) Tj
T*
(calculating the height of a paragraph of line-wrapped text without touching the DOM . The usual) Tj
T*
(way of doing this is to render the text and measure its dimensions, but this is extremely) Tj
T*
(expensive. Pretext uses an array of clever tricks to make this much, much faster, which enables) Tj
T*
(all sorts of new text rendering effects in browser applications. Here's one demo that shows the) Tj
T*
(kind of things this makes possible: The key to how this works is the way it separates) Tj
T*
(calculations into a call to a prepare\(\) function followed by multiple calls to layout\(\) . The) Tj
T*
(prepare\(\) function splits the input text into segments \(effectively words, but it can take) Tj
T*
(things like soft hyphens and non-latin character sequences and emoji into account as well\) and) Tj
T*
(measures those using an off-screen canvas, then caches the results. This is comparatively) Tj
T*
(expensive but only runs once. The layout\(\) function can then emulate the word-wrapping logic in) Tj
T*
(browsers to figure out how many wrapped lines the text will occupy at a specified width...) Tj
T*
