(15. 6o6 v1.1: Faster 6502-on-6502 virtualization for a C64/Apple II Apple-1 emulator) Tj
T*
(Source: Old Vintage Computing Research | Published: 2026-03-28T19:30:00.000-07:00) Tj
T*
(Link: https://oldvcr.blogspot.com/2026/03/6o6-v11-faster-6502-on-6502.html) Tj
T*
(I'm doing periodic updates on some of my long-term projects, one of them being 6o6, a fully) Tj
T*
(virtualized NMOS 6502 CPU core that runs on a 6502 written in 6502 assembly language. 6o6) Tj
T*
(implements a completely abstracted memory model and a fully controlled execution environment,) Tj
T*
(but by using the host's ALU and providing a primitive means of instruction fusion it can be) Tj
T*
(faster than a naďve interpreter. This library was something I wrote over two decades earlier) Tj
T*
(for my KIM-1 emulator project for the Commodore 64, and relatively recently I open-sourced and) Tj
T*
(discussed it in detail . It runs on just about any 6502-based system with sufficient memory.) Tj
T*
(For this update I made some efficiency improvements to addressing modes, trimmed an instruction) Tj
T*
(out of the hot path, provided an option for even more control of the 6502 interrupt flag and) Tj
T*
(implemented a faster lane for direct stores to 6502 zero page \(as well as the usual custodial) Tj
T*
(and documentation updates\). And, of course, any complex library needs a suite of examples, and) Tj
T*
(of course, any update to a complex library demands new examples to play with too. So, given) Tj
T*
(that this year is Apple's 50th anniversary \(and, as it happens, my own 50th year...) Tj
T*
() Tj
